@node "HowToInstall" "How To Install?"

@{MS "How To Install?"}

Please use the included installer script to install the archive and the drivers.@{par}

@{b}Manual installation may cause unexpected problems. The automatic
installation ensures a proper, clean and working installation.@{ub}

@endnode
@node "QuickStart" "Quick Start"

@{MS "Quick Start"}

After installation you should restart the system if an old version is running in
background. It's also possible to quit all IRCom supporting applications and
perfrom an "avail flush" inside a shell window, but restarting is much easier.@{par}

The first step is to configure your IR hardware. Double click the IRComPrefs
icon within the IRCom drawer. Select new and insert the hardware driver. If you
use an "IRTrans" module, then use "irtrans.device" and for "IgorPlug USB (AVR)"
use "igorplug.device".@{par}

The hardware unit is "0". If you want to use more than one piece of the same
hardware, then use "1" for the second and so on.@{par}

Some drivers need additional information on how they are connected. If no
additional port driver is needed leave this field empty. Known combinations will
be filled automatically by the preferences tool. So for IRTrans the preferences
tool automatically selects "serialirtrans.device" as port driver. If you want to
connect a serial IRTrans, then override the name with the driver of your serial
device.@{par}

The "Test" button allows to check if the driver starts up correct. If it's not
working, then check connection. If the driver is connected though USB, then
check if Poseidon is aware of the new classes and if the usb device is correctly
bond to the usb driver class. Also note that device drivers need to be written
in lower case.@{par}

By using the save button the configuration will be stored and the configuration
tool will be closed.@{par}

Since you surely don't own one of the included remote controls you need to tell
IRCom your remote specifications. This can be done by using the
IRComRemoteEditor. If you set up the hardware properly than the remote editor
will startup without any error. It shows the type of hardware and the the status
field shows that learning mode is disabled.@{par}

Activate the learn mode. Depending on the type of hardware different modes are
available. If the option timing is available, then use it, because learning the
timing is the best way to start. If not, then select normal.@{par}

Now the status field changes and after a short pause it will signal that the
driver is ready. Push the first key on remote and an entry should appear inside
the key list. The name gadget activates, so you can straight enter a proper name
for the key. Then simply push the next key and repeat until the remote is complete.@{par}

If you choosed "timing" learn mode, then you may noticed that the mode changed
after pressing the first remote key. This is because after learning the fast
mode will be used and the timing learned by the first key will be used as base
for the following. So only the data stream needs to be captured.@{par}

After all you should set-up the field right top in the window and then use the
menu to save the remote. Default name will be "vendorname-remotename" which will
be fine in the most cases.@{par}

After closing the editor the remote can by used by any IRCom Application and tool.@{par}

@endnode
