@node "FAQS" "Questions, Solutions and Tips!"

@{MS "Questions, Solutions and Tips!"}

@{jcenter}@{"What is IRCom?" link "FAQSIRCom"}@{par}
@{"What means 'Key or Remote in IRCom style'?" link "FAQSBATCHNAME"}@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSIRCom" "What is IRCom?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is IRCom?"}

IRCom stands for "Infra Red Communication" and is an universal driver for IR hardware.

@endnode
@node "FAQSBATCHNAME" "What means 'Key or Remote in IRCom style'?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What means 'Key or Remote in IRCom style'?"}

To specify key in Applications and AmigaDOS I invented the IRCom style. All applications
must use this format to avoid users beeing confused about the correct definition.@{par}

The key naming is done by ordinary text which is parted by usind \@.
"play\@remote\@cdplayer" for example is causing each application to search the
key database for the "play" key. The search will be done in the Remote named
"remote" if the remote is part of the device "cdplayer".@{par}

This may sound confusing, but it isn't complicated. Most programms handle the
last two arguments identicaly. A key named "play\@remote" would be the same as
the key "play\@cdplayer". The standard allows to skip any section of the key
name.@{par}

"play" searches for the first key with the name "Play" inside the data base.
"play\@cdp-c425" searches inside a specific device for this key. Some programm
even just need a remote name. Such case looks like this: "\@cdp-c425".
@{"IRComTranslate" link "IRComTranslate"} is a tool which allows such remote
specification.@{par}

If you don't know how you named your remote or the rmeote keys, then use the
@{"IRComRemoteEditor" link "IRComRemoteEditor"} and load the remote preset. The
second way is to use the @{"IRComDump" link "IRComDump"} shell command.@{par}

@endnode

@node "IRComTools" "IRCom Tools"

@{MS "IRCom Tools"}

The IRCom Tools are a collection of useful tools for the IRCom Driver system.@{par}

Currently the following tools are included:
@{code}
@{JCENTER}@{"IRComWait" link "IRComWait"}
@{"IRComSend" link "IRComSend"}
@{"IRComDump" link "IRComDump"}
@{"IRComTranslate" link "IRComTranslate"}

@endnode
@node "IRComWait" "IRCom Tools - IRComWait"

@{MS "IRComWait"}

IRComWait is an AmigaDOS program which allows to wait for specific IR signals.
This allows to create dos script which react to specific remote key with specific
actions.@{par}

Template: UNIT=U/K/N,KEYS/A/M@{par}

Unit,U : IRCom unit is the IRCom hardware number as set in @{"IRComPrefs" link "IRComPrefs"}. Defauls is 0 (first config).@{par}
KEYS   : Specifies always a IR key in @{"IRCom Style" link "FAQSBATCHNAME"} and result code pair.@{par}

Examples:@{par}

IRComWait play\@CDP-C425 5@{par}

Waits for the "Play" key pressed on the remote of the cd player "CDP-C425".
If that key is pressed the wait returns with result code 5.@{par}

IRComWait play\@CDP-C425 5 stop\@CDP-C425 10@{par}

Waits for the "Play" or "Stop" key pressed on the remote of the cd player
"CDP-C425". If that key is "Play" pressed the wait returns with result code 5,
if it's "Stop" it returns 10.@{par}

IRComWait  1\@CDP-C425 10 \@CDP-C425 25@{par}

Any key will return a value of 25, expect the "1" key which returns a 10. It's
important to know that the first key in the chain will be checked first. If you
swap the key pairs you would always get 25 and the "1" would have no effect at
all.@{par}

IRComWait  Stop\@CDP-C425 10 Play\@Playstation2 25\@{par}

This is just an example with to different remotes.@{par}

@endnode
@node "IRComSend" "IRCom Tools - IRComSend"

@{MS "IRComSend"}

IRComWait is an AmigaDOS program which allows to send specific IR signals.
This allows to control devices by using simple AmigaDos Scripts.@{par}

Template: UNIT=U/K/N,KEYS/A/M@{par}

Unit,U : IRCom unit is the IRCom hardware number as set in @{"IRComPrefs" link "IRComPrefs"}. Defauls is 0 (first config).@{par}
KEYS   : Specifies always an IR key in @{"IRCom Style" link "FAQSBATCHNAME"}@{par}

Examples:@{par}

IRComSend play\@CDP-C425@{par}

Sends the "play" signal for the CD-player "CDP-C425".

IRComSend ">10\@CDP-C425" 1\@CDP-C425 2\@CDP-C425@{par}

Sends the ">10" key followed by a "1" and a "2". The CD player will play tack 12.@{par}

IRComSend program\@CDP-C425 1\@CDP-C425 7\@CDP-C425 9\@CDP-C425 ">10\@CDP-C425" 1\@CDP-C425 2\@CDP-C425 play\@CDP-C425 @{par}

Now this is getting cool! We activate the cd player program mode and program the
tracks 1, 7, 9 and 12. Finaly we play these tracks by starting the program.@{par}

@endnode
@node "IRComTranslate" "IRCom Tools - IRComTranslate"

@{MS "IRComTranslate"}

IRComWait is an AmigaDOS program which allows to translate specific IR signals.@{par}

This allows to replace lost remote controls or use old remotes as programmable remotes.@{par}

Template: UNIT=U/K/N,KEYS/A/M@{par}

Unit,U : IRCom unit is the IRCom hardware number as set in @{"IRComPrefs" link "IRComPrefs"}. Defauls is 0 (first config).@{par}
KEYS   : Specifies always a pair of IR keys or remotes in @{"IRCom Style" link "FAQSBATCHNAME"}@{par}

Examples:@{par}

IRComTranslate \@playstation2 \@CDP-C425@{par}

The Playstation2 remote can now be used to control the CD player. The ir hardware is
converting the incomming signal by using the data base and sends out the new signal the CD-Player understands.@{par}

IRComTranslate select\@Playstation2 DiscSkip\@CDP-C425 \@playstation2 \@CDP-C425@{par}

The CD-player is a changer and the "DiscSkip" key is missing on Playstation2
remote. So we translate it by hand. If the "Select" key is pressed an "DiscSkip"
is transmitted. If not, than we translate it like in the example before.@{par}

This allows to combine the most important functions from different remotes to a
lets say old remote, where the device isn't around anymore. If there are many
specical cases it may be useful to learn the replacement remote and name the key
by the desired functions. This prevents from making complicated translate
command. Like the example above you could name the select key "DiscSkip" in the
Playstation2 configuration and the translator will automatically pick the right
send out key.@{par}

@endnode
@node "IRComDump" "IRCom Tools - IRComDump"

@{MS "IRComDump"}

IRComWait is an AmigaDOS program which allows to display received ir signals.
This allows to get the defined key names easily.@{par}

Template: UNIT=U/K/N@{par}

Unit,U : IRCom unit is the IRCom hardware number as set in @{"IRComPrefs" link "IRComPrefs"}. Defauls is 0 (first config).@{par}

Examples:@{par}

IRComDump@{par}

The IR-Data will be shown as shell output.

@endnode
@node "IRComPrefs" "IRComPrefs"

@{MS "IRComPrefs"}

IRcomDump is a configuration tool which allows to bind IR receiver and sender to
the IRCom driver system.@{par}

The usage is very easy. Each Entry in list is a hardware that should be used.
Just create an entry for each hardware.@{par}

The hardware driver defines the device itself. e.g. "irtrans.device" or
"igorplug.device". Since these drivers may support more than one module at the
same time you can specify a unit. The first hardware gets a "0", the second a
"1" and so on.@{par}

Interface drivers are drivers required to interact with the hardware. If for
example the IRTrans module is connected via serial port, then you need to
specify that port and the specific unit. This may be "serial.device". The
interface number is the port number the ir hardware is connected to. This is
required to set correctly when dealing with multi io cards.@{par}

The IRCom unit in the list is important. All programs using IRCom will allow to
specify this number. So if you specify a "0" the used hardware is always the
first in list. If there are two devices in list, then you can specify unit 0 and
1 as IRCom unit.@{par}

As you can see IRComPrefs are simply making the usage easier. Instead of
defining devices and units for each application or shell tool you just specify a
number and since programs are using unit 0 as default, you don't even need to
config anything else after leaving this setup.@{par}

The gadget "Test..." tries to open the current selected hardware as an
application would do. It just allows to check the correct set-up. After saving
the preferences you configuration is available to all IRCom applications.@{par}

@{b}Please note, that programs currently running in background won't be effected
and may need to be restarted to use the up to date configuration. @{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "IRComRemoteEditor" "IRCom Tools - IRComRemoteEditor"

@{MS "IRComRemoteEditor"}

The IRComRemoteEditor in simple words is a easy and comfortable way to learn a
remote control. Once a remote is store in the data base it can be used with all
applications.@{par}

In the right top you find text fields to identify the remote. This information
will be used to find specific entries in the data base.@{par}

In the top left the current hardware and it's state is shown. It's also possible
to select the learning mode. The types and number of learning modes is different
from hardware to hardware. Many of these modes are very specific and should only
be used if you know what you're doing.@{par}

Timing@{par}

The first key is used to identify the ir key timing. After learning the timing
the remote editor switches to normal learn mode. This mode only learns the IR
stream which is much faster and normally all key on a remote use the same
tining. Some times learning the timing fails, so if you learn a key timing and
the key works as desired, you can be sure the other keys will work, because the
timing is reused.@{par}

Fast@{par}

The time of the current key will be used as base timing for any keys learned by using this mode.

Normal@{par}

This mode is learning the timing for any key. If the ir module does not support
timings, then only the data stream will be read.@{par}

@endnode

@node "IRComDrivers" "IRCom Drivers"

@{MS "IRCom Drivers"}

@{JCENTER}Drivers for the following devices are included:@{par}
@{code}
@{JCENTER}@{"IRTrans" link "IRComDriverIRTrans"}@{par}
@{"IgorPlug USB (AVR)" link "IRComDriverIgorPlug"}@{par}
@{"SimpleRxd" link "IRComDriverSimpleRxd"}@{par}

@endnode

@node "IRComDriverIRTrans" "IRCom Device Driver - IRTrans"

@{MS "IRTrans"}

The IRTrans device is the ferrari of the available ir modules. It is developed
by @{b}Marcus Müller@{ub}. The price is aound 100 Euro, but it's worth it. The
IRTrans is the most powerful IR-module available and supports nearly any remote
control in receiving and sending.@{par}

The current driver was tested with the USB IRTrans. The serial version should
work, too. Anyway keep me informed if you try the serial version.@{par}

Additional information on the IRTrans and it's developer can be found here:
@{"http://www.irtrans.de/" system "c:OpenURL http://www.irtrans.de/ >con://///AUTO/WAIT/CLOSE"}@{par}

Within the @{"IRComPrefs" link "IRComPrefs"} you need to specify
"irtrans.device" as hardware driver. The inferface driver will be set
automatically as "serialirtrans.device"@{par}

@{b}Please note that the "serialirtrans.device" isn't available as single file.
It will be created on the fly by the "irtrans.class".@{ub}@{par}

If there is any problem with the configuration, then check your Poseidon
configuration (Trident). When using MorphOS you'll find the USB configuration
within the system preferences.@{par}

"IRTrans USB" should be displayed in the devices section. The device should be
bond to "irtrans.class". If the device is missing, then check if it is connected
correct. If the binding is missing, then Poseidon does't know anything about the
new "irtrans.class". In such case select "classes" and then push the "Dir Scan"
button. Make sure you save the updated list along with the new configuration.@{par}

There is an additional IRTrans configuration utitlity available, which replaces
the windows version. Specific information on all functions can be found inside
the IRTrans manual.@{par}

@{b}Please note that up to know the uhciusb.device delivered with MorphOS isn't
compatible with the IRTrans. Using an NEC based USB card with OHCI controller
may be a solution to work around this problem.@{ub}

@endnode
@node "IRComDriverIgorPlug" "IRCom Device Driver - IgorPlug USB (AVR)"

@{MS "IgorPlug USB (AVR)"}

The IgorPlug device is a simple, small and compact device which allows receiving
of IR signals by using the usb port. The hardware was made by @{b}Igor
Cesko@{ub}.@{par}

This hardware is realy cheap. It's available for around 10 euro and it's
possible to build the hardware on your own. Please note, that several shops are
selling the the IgorPlug hardware without having a proper licence. So if you buy
a ready to run device consider donating some money to the man who did the job
for real.@{par}

Additional information about IgorPlug and Developer can be found here:
@{"http://www.cesko.host.sk/" system "c:OpenURL http://www.cesko.host.sk/ >con://///AUTO/WAIT/CLOSE"}@{par}

The IgorPlug is only able to receive signals. Sending is out of scope.@{par}

As far as I know there is a serial version of the IgorPlug. I didn't had the
chance to check that version out, but in theory it should work. Well, if you're
interested in using a serial version, you should consider of donating a version
just to ensure it is work properly.@{par}

Within the @{"IRComPrefs" link "IRComPrefs"} you need to specify the
"igorplug.device" as hardware driver. The interface driver will be set to
"serialigorplug.device" automaticaly.@{par}

@{b}Please note that the "serialigorplug.device" isn't available as single file.
It will be created on the fly by the "irtrans.class".@{ub}@{par}

"IgorPlug-USB (AVR)" should be displayed in the devices section. The device should be
bond to "igorplug.class". If the device is missing, then check if it is connected
correct. If the binding is missing, then Poseidon does't know anything about the
new "igorplug.class". In such case select "classes" and then push the "Dir Scan"
button. Make sure you save the updated list along with the new configuration.@{par}

@endnode

@node "IRComDriverSimpleRxd" "IRCom Device Driver - SimpleRxd"

@{MS "SimpleRxd"}

The SimpleRxd module was developed by @{b}Carsten Siegner@{ub}. Practicaly it's an
IR-receiver connected to the data in pin of the serial port.@{par}

The data received by the driver isn't 100% constant. The data stream also don't
contain any real ir data. Depending on the remote it's working more or less and
you can wait for some specific.@{par}

The baud rate can be defined by specifing it as interface driver argument inside
the @{"IRComPrefs" link "IRComPrefs"}.@{par}

Example:@{par}

Baud 9600@{par}

@{b}This driver is more or less an example on how to code a IRCom driver and the
source code is available within the SDK.@{ub}@{par}

@endnode


